

<html>
<head>
<title>Statistical Inference II Classnote</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=right><font size=-2>[Stat Inf II
classnotes, ISI, Kolkata]
</td></tr></table>
<h1>Properties of tests</h1>




<h3>Are these tests any "good"?</h3>

So far we have presented a number of tests based on ad hoc justification
only. The natuaral question that arises now is how "good" are they?


<hr>
<table width=100% bgcolor="#cccccc">
<tr><td align=center><b><i>Digression:
Randomised tests
</b></i></td></tr></table>
<hr>

Suppose that we have data, X, taking values in some sample space, S. We
also have two hypotheses, H<sub>0</sub> and H<sub>1</sub>, that we want to
test. <p>

A (non-randomised) test is a function

<blockquote>
&phi; : S 
          <img src=
          "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
          align=middle>
          
           {"accept H<sub>0</sub>", "reject
H<sub>0</sub>"}
</blockquote>

<p>

A <i>randomised</i> test is a generalisation of this concept that allows
mixtures of "accept" and "reject". Thus, for instance, 

<blockquote>
"1/3 accept+ 2/3 reject"
</blockquote>

mean

<blockquote>
"toss a coin (independently of the data) with P(head) = 2/3. If
you get a head, then reject, else accept."
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise TEST.1:</font></b> 
   Suppose that X ~ Binomial(10,p). We want to test 
   
   <blockquote>
   H<sub>0</sub>: p = 1/2 Vs. H<sub>1</sub>: p  &gt;  1/2
   </blockquote>
   
   Consider the following randomised test:
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <table border=0>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   &phi;(x)
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
    accept if x = 0,...,6
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   0.25 accept + 0.75 reject if x=7
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   reject if x=8,9,10
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   </table>
   
   </blockquote>
   
   Compute P(type I error) for this test. Show that no non-randomised test
   can achieve this P(type I error).
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
This is the main reason why randomised tests are used. They can achieve
values of P(type I error) unachievable by nonrandomised tests. <p>
If we denote "accept H<sub>0</sub>" by 0, and "reject H<sub>0</sub>" by 1,
then a non-randomised test is a function

<blockquote>
&phi;: S 
         <img src=
         "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
         align=middle>
         
          {0,1}
</blockquote>

In this notation a randomised test is a function

<blockquote>
&phi;: S 
         <img src=
         "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
         align=middle>
         
          [0,1]
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   The test in the last exercise, for instance, is
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <table border=0>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   &phi;(x)
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
    0 if x = 0,...,6
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   0.75  if x=7
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   1 if x=8,9,10
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   </table>
   
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
Notice that in this notation E(&phi;) is the chance that we reject
H<sub>0</sub>. 

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise TEST.2:</font></b> 
   Fix any &alpha; in [0,1]. Conside the "coin toss test"
   
   <blockquote>
   &phi;(x) = &alpha;   for all x in S.
   
   
   </blockquote>
   
   Describe it in words. Compute its level  (i.e., P(type I error)) and power.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<hr>
<table width=100% bgcolor="#cccccc">
<tr><td align=center><b><i>Digression over
</i></b></td></tr></table>
<hr>



<h4>Unbiasedness</h4>

Let &phi; and &xi; be two (randomised) tests. To compare between them
we need to compare probabilities of both types of errors. If &phi; has
<i>both</i> the probabilities less than those of &xi;, then of course
&phi; is a better test than &xi;. In this case, we shall say that
&phi; beats &xi;. 
<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Definition:</b>

Call a test &phi; <i>unbiased</i> if it cannot be beaten by a coin toss test.

</td></tr></table>


<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise TEST.3:</font></b> 
   Suppose that I am testing a simple H<sub>0</sub> Vs a
   simple H<sub>1</sub>. Let &phi; be a test with 
   
   <blockquote>
   
   
   <table border=0>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   E(&phi;)
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
    0.05 under H<sub>0</sub>
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   <tr>
   <td align=right>
   
   </td>
   <td>
   =
   </td>
   <td align=left>
   0.03 under H<sub>1</sub>
   </td>
   </tr>
   
   
   </table>
   
   
   </blockquote>
   
   Is this test unbiased? 
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise TEST.4:</font></b> 
   Show that a test &phi; is unbiased iff 
   
   <blockquote>
   sup<sub>0</sub> E(&phi;) 
                            <img src=
                            "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                            align=top>
                            
                             sup<sub>1</sub> E(&phi;)
   </blockquote>
   
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p> Many authors use this as the definition of unbiasedness. However, we
would suggest that you remember the definition of unbiasedness that we
have given earlier in terms of the coin toss test. That one is easier to
remember and is more intuitive.<p>
An estimator that is biased may be  an estimator worth considering. But a
testr that is not 
unbiased is worthless. Even a simple coin toss outpefroms it. <p>
We want to show that all the tests that we performed so far are
unbiased. This will follow from the theorem below.
<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Theorem:</b>

Suppose we have data

<blockquote>
X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>
</blockquote>

from a location family F(x-&theta;). We want to test 

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: &theta; = 0 Vs &theta;  &gt; 0.
</blockquote>

Suppose we have a test &phi; that rejects H<sub>0</sub> iff 
T(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>) 
                                   <img src=
                                   "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                   align=top>
                                   
                                    c, for some test statistic T(.)
and some critical value c. If for all b 
                                        <img src=
                                        "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                        align=top>
                                        
                                         0,

<blockquote>
T(X<sub>1</sub>+b,...,X<sub>n</sub>+b) 
                                       <img src=
                                       "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                       align=top>
                                       
                                       
T(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>)
</blockquote>

then &phi; is an unbiased test.

</td></tr></table>

<p>

<table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
<td>
<b><i>Proof:</i></b> 
Simple straightforward computation, that we shall split up into
two exercises.
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise TEST.5:</font></b> 
   
   Show that if b 
                  <img src=
                  "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                  align=top>
                  
                   0, then
   
   <blockquote>
   T(X<sub>1</sub>+b,...,X<sub>n</sub>+b) 
                                          <img src=
                                          "resources/statinf2/sgeq.png"
                                          align=top>
                                          
                                          
   T(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>)
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise TEST.6:</font></b> 
   Show that
   
   <blockquote>
   T(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>) under H<sub>1</sub>
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/sgeq.png"
   align=top>
   
   
   T(X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>n</sub>) under H<sub>0</sub>
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
Hence conclude the theorem.

<img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>


<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise TEST.7:</font></b> 
   Show that the sign test is unbiased.
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

We can similarly state and prove a theorem for scale family or two sample
problems. 








